{{Underlinked|date=March 2014}}
{{Political corruption sidebar|image=[[File:Flag of Tanzania.svg|150 px]]}}
Both grand and petty corruption are serious problems in [[Tanzania]] yet various comprehensive laws are in place to prevent corruption. It is largely due to a weak internal control and low or non-compliance with anti-corruption regulations within different government agencies. For instance, public procurement, taxation, and customs service are areas that are prone to corruption. Foreign companies have identified that corruption within those sectors poses potential obstacles for doing business in Tanzania as bribery is often demanded.<ref>{{cite web|title= Tanzania Corruption Profile|url=http://www.business-anti-corruption.com/country-profiles/sub-saharan-africa/tanzania/show-all.aspx|publisher=Business Anti-Corruption Portal|accessdate= 14 July 2015}}</ref> 
[[File:Tanzania from above.jpg|thumb|Tanzania from above]]
It is also believed that the existing large informal sector, amount 48.1% of GDP, is associated with cumbersome business registration process which have created opportunities for corruption.<ref>{{cite web|title=Size and contribution of the informal sector|url=http://www.ippmedia.com/frontend/?l=52934|publisher=IPP Media|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>

