The [[Italian language|Italian]] term '''papello'''<ref>From ''papýrus'' in [[Latin language|Latin]] and ''πάπυρος'' (''pàpyros'') in [[Ancient Greek]], from which derive modern terms ''paper'', ''papier'' ([[French language|French]]) and ''papel'' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]).</ref> (in {{lang-scn|Papeddu}}) indicates "a long and detailed paper note, a letter or a complaint" containing indications.<ref>{{it icon}}
 [http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2009/luglio/20/Papellu_co_9_090720011.shtml ''Papellu''], quoted by [[Vincenzo Consolo]] in ''La parola''. Corriere della sera. Archivio storico. 20 luglio 2009.</ref>

In Italian press since [[2000s (decade)|2000s]], the term is referred to the [[State-Mafia Pact]] occurred during [[1990s (decade)|1990s]]. A copy of the ''papello'' was consigned to magistrates by [[Massimo Ciancimino]] through his lawyer, [[Francesca Russo]], on 15 October 2009.

