ith [[Eudokia Makrembolitissa]]; Emperor Alexios I Komnenos had him blinded after charging him with treason |<ref name= "Holmes p. 222">{{harvnb|Holmes|2005|p=222}}</ref> |- |{{sortname|Romanos IV|Diogenes|Romanos IV Diogenes}} |1072 |Blinded |[[Andronikos Doukas (cousin of Michael VII)|Andronikos Doukas]] had Romanos IV Diogenes blinded after tricking him into stepping down as emperor |<ref name= "Norwich p. 357">{{harvnb|Norwich|1993|p=357}}</ref> |- |[[Heraklonas]] |641 |{{sort|Nose|Nose slit}} |Overthrown, disfigured and exiled by supporters of [[Constans II (Byzantine Empire)|Constans II]] |<ref name= "Theophanes p. 41">[[#refTheophanes1982|Theophanes 1982]], p.41.</ref> |- |{{sortname|Theophylact,||Theophylact (son of Michael I)}} Staurakios and Niketas (the future [[Patriarch Ignatius of Constantinople|Patriarch Ignatius]] |813 |Castrated |Sons of [[Michael I Rhangabe]], they were castrated after his overthrow by [[Leo V the Armenian]] |<ref>{{harvnb|Treadgold|1988|pp=188–189}}</ref> |- |[[Justinian II]] |695 |{{sort|Nose|Nose cut off}} |Overthrown, disfigured and exiled by supporters of [[Leontios]] |<ref name= "Ostrogorski p. 124"/> |- |[[Alexios Komnenos (protosebastos)|Alexios Komnenos]] |1182 |{{sort|Blinded|Blinded, possibly castrated}} |''De facto'' regent for [[Alexios II Komnenos]], overthrown by the usurper [[Andronikos I Komnenos]] | |- |{{sortname|John IV|Laskaris|John IV Laskaris}} |1261 |Blinded |Made emperor at seven years old, he was overthrown and blinded when he was eleven years old |<ref name= "Hackel p. 71">{{harvnb|Hackel|2001|p=71}}</ref> |- |{{sortname|Basil|Lekapenos}} |{{sort|920|920–944}}{{#tag:ref|Basil Lekapenos was castrated as an infant sometime during Emperor [[Romanos I Lekapenos]]'s rule (920–944). However, there is no date on either the castration or on when he was born.|group="A"}} |Castrated |As an infant he was castrated for being born an illegitimate son to Emperor Romanos I Lekapenos |<ref name= "Norwich p. 167"/> |- |[[